    {
      "id": "q-10",
      "type": "long",
      "question": "Define orthogonal matrix. Prove that if A is orthogonal, then det(A) = \u00b11 and A\u207b\u00b9 = A\u1d40.",
      "keyPoints": [
        "Orthogonal matrix: A\u1d40A = AA\u1d40 = I",
        "Take det: det(A\u1d40A) = det(A\u1d40)det(A) = (det(A))\u00b2 = det(I) = 1",
        "Thus det(A) = \u00b11",
        "From A\u1d40A = I, multiply by A\u207b\u00b9: A\u1d40 = A\u207b\u00b9",
        "Thus inverse equals transpose: A\u207b\u00b9 = A\u1d40"
